{{Infobox film | name = Noesa Penida | image = | image_size = | border = | alt = | caption = | director = [[Andjar Asmara]] | producer =[[The Teng Chun]] | screenplay = Andjar Asmara | narrator = | starring ={{plain list| *[[Ratna Asmara]] *[[Astaman]] *Rd Ismail *[[Ali Joego]] }} | music = | cinematography = | editing = | studio = New Java Industrial Film | distributor = | released = {{Film date|df=yes|1941|||Dutch East Indies}} | runtime = | country = [[Dutch East Indies]] | language = Indonesian | budget = | gross = }} '''''Noesa Penida''''' ({{IPA-id|nuˈsa pəˈnida|}}; [[EYD|Perfected Spelling]] '''''Nusa Penida''''') is a 1941 film from the [[Dutch East Indies]] (present-day Indonesia) which was directed by [[Andjar Asmara]] and produced by [[The Teng Chun]] of Java Industrial FIlm. It tells of a love triangle between two brothers, born to a commoner, and a noble woman.
==Plot== On the island of [[Nusa Penida]], two common-born brothers (Jaya and I Pageh) are friends with Pandansari, daughter of the king. When the king is murdered, Pandansari goes into hiding with her father's loyal manservant I Murda. Jaya, I Pageh, and Pandansari are soon entangled in a [[love triangle]], one which is rendered more difficult owing to differences in [[Balinese caste system|caste]]. Ultimately, after rumors emerge that Jaya has been killed, Pandansari chooses I Pageh.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Noesa Penida}}
==Production== [[File:The Teng Chun filming Noesa Penida.jpg|thumb|The Teng Chun]] ''Noesa Penida'' was produced by [[The Teng Chun]] for his company New Java Industrial Film (New JIF). It was written and directed by [[Andjar Asmara]], a former journalist and stage-writer who had made his directorial debut the preceding year with ''[[Kartinah]]''.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Noesa Penida}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Abisin Abbas}}</ref> HB Angin handled artistic direction.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Kredit Noesa Penida}} Andjar and his wife, [[Ratna Asmara|Ratna]], each earned 1,000 [[Netherlands Indies gulden|gulden]] for their roles in the film; this was several times the wages of [[Roekiah]] and [[Kartolo]], stars at New JIF's competitor [[Tan's Film]].{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=213}}
The film starred Ratna Asmara, as well as [[Astaman]], Rd Ismail, and [[Ali Joego]].{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Noesa Penida}} Ratna and Astaman, both with a background as stage performers, had previously worked with Andjar in ''Kartinah''.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Kartinah}}
==Release and reception== ''Noesa Penida'' was released in 1941. A [[35 mm]] copy of the film is stored at [[Sinematek Indonesia]] in [[Jakarta]].{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Noesa Penida}}
''Noesa Penida'' has been adapted several times. During its initial run it was brought to the stage by various troupes.{{sfn|Mahayana|2005|p=438}} From 30 June to 14 September 1942 Andjar [[List of literary works published in Asia Raja|published]] a serialization of the film in the newspaper ''[[Asia Raja]]''.{{sfn|Mahayana|2007|pp=201–202}} It was compiled as a novel in 1950.{{sfn|Mahayana|Sofyan|Dian|1995|pp=86–88}} The film was remade in 1988 as ''Noesa Penida (Pelangi Kasih Pandansari)'' (''Noesa Penida (Pandansari's Rainbow of Love)''). Directed by Galeb Husein and with adaptations by [[Asrul Sani]], the remake starred Ida Ayu Made Diastini, Ray Sahetapy, and Sutopo HS.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Noesa Penida (Pelangi Kasih Pandansari)}}
