[[File:Alexandra Konofalskaya.jpg|thumb|Alexandra Konofalskaya performing sand animation]]
'''Sand animation''' is the manipulation of sand to create [[animation]]. In [[performance art]] an artist creates a series of images using [[sand]], a process which is achieved by applying sand to a surface and then rendering images by drawing lines and figures in the sand with one's hands. A sand animation performer will often use the aid of an [[overhead projector]] or [[lightbox]] (similar to one used by photographers to view [[Reversal film|translucent films]]). To make an animated film, sand is moved on a backlit or frontlit piece of glass to create each frame.
== History == Techniques for animating with sand were pioneered by [[Caroline Leaf]] when she was an undergraduate art student at [[Harvard University]] in 1968.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nfb.ca/film/handcrafted_cinema|title=Hand-Crafted Cinema Animation Workshop with Caroline Leaf|last=Roberts|first=Eric|year=1998|publisher=National Film Board of Canada|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref> She created her first film, ''Sand, or Peter and the Wolf'' (1968), by dumping beach sand on a light box and manipulating the grains to build figures, textures and movement frame-by-frame.<ref name="HARV">{{cite web|url=http://hcl.harvard.edu/hfa/films/2012octdec/leaf.html|title=The Animated Art of Caroline Leaf|date=November 5, 2012|work=Film Series / Events|publisher=Harvard College Library|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref> In the 1970s, [[Eli Noyes]], another Harvard graduate, created the noted ''Sandman'' short film (1973) <ref>{{cite journal | last=Griffin | first=George | title=Cartoon, Anti-Cartoon | journal=The American Animated Cartoon | editor=Donald Peary and Gerald Peary | year=1980 | page=261-268}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmpreservation.org/preserved-films/2016-federal-grant-winners|title=Sandman|work=2016 Federal Grant Winners|publisher=National Film Preservation Foundation|accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref> and the ''Sand Alphabet'' (1974) which became a feature on the children's educational television program ''Sesame Street''.<ref>{{cite journal | author=Educational Film Library Association | title=Motion pictures in education | journal=Sightlines | year=1976 | volume=10-11 | page=62}}</ref> In 1977, ''[[The Sand Castle (film)|The Sand Castle]]'' by Dutch-Canadian animator [[Co Hoedeman]] won the [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film]]. <ref name=evans>{{cite book|last=Evans|first=Gary|title=In the National Interest: A Chronicle of the National Film Board of Canada from 1949 to 1989|publisher=[[University of Toronto Press]]|isbn=978-0802068330|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gM2j0CN64isC&pg=PA232&dq=The+Sand+Castle+Co+Hoedeman#v=onepage&q=The%20Sand%20Castle%20Co%20Hoedeman&f=false|accessdate=19 March 2012|page=232|date=30 September 1991}}</ref>
==Notable artists== <!--NOTE: All persons listed below must have English Wikipedia articles and reliable independent sources.--> * [[Ferenc Cakó]] * [[Su Dabao]] * [[Co Hoedeman]] * [[Alexandra Konofalskaya]] * [[Caroline Leaf]] * [[Eli Noyes]] * [[Kseniya Simonova]] * [[Ilana Yahav]] <!--NOTE: All persons listed above must have English Wikipedia articles and reliable independent sources.-->
